The security hierarchy.

Unity catalog's permission model is a strict tree — metastore, then catalog, then schema, then the objects. And the central rule is that privileges granted at any level inherit to everything below.

Two privileges gate access at every level above an object. Use-catalog on a catalog — without it, you can't even see the schemas inside. And use-schema on a schema — without it, you can't see the tables inside.

This leads to the most common exam trap. A grant of select on a single table is useless on its own if the principal lacks use-catalog on the catalog and use-schema on the schema. So the answer that omits use-catalog or use-schema is the wrong answer. You always need the chain — use-catalog, use-schema, and then select.

One shortcut, and one caution. Granting select on a whole schema gives select on every existing and future table in it — powerful, but a foot-gun. For production, prefer narrower, more deliberate grants.
